        "created_at": "2026-01-26T05:28:01.461Z",
        "cooked": "<p>My primary device is a PC. In all chats, message auto-delete is set to \u201c1 day.\u201d When I open Signal on my phone, where background activity for the app is disabled, message synchronization starts.</p>\n<p>During this process, it looks as if the entire conversation is being re-created very quickly. All messages sent by me and the other person flash on the screen, including messages that were supposedly sent <em>before</em> the deletion deadline.</p>\n<p>Example: I haven\u2019t opened the app on my phone for three days. During synchronization, messages from all three days are restored. I can clearly see messages flashing from 3, 2, and 1 days ago. This strongly suggests that they are being fetched from Signal\u2019s servers, where they are apparently still stored.</p>\n<p>But why are they there at all if I explicitly set them to be deleted?</p>\n<p>After synchronization finishes, I cannot find these messages via search because they are marked as deleted. However, I literally saw them with my own eyes during the sync process.</p>\n<p>Please explain how this mechanism works.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 5,
        "updated_at": "2026-01-26T05:45:03.888Z",
        "reply_count": 0,
